 *    Arenas do NOT run destructors. If you allocate objects with
 *    cleanup requirements (file handles, locks), you must manually
 *    clean them up before reset/destroy.
 * 
 * 3. Alignment Correctness:
 *    The arena respects @alignof(T) automatically. Mixed-type
 *    allocations are safe (no alignment violations).
 * 
 * 4. Thread Safety:
 *    Arenas are NOT thread-safe. Use one arena per thread, or
 *    wrap in a mutex for shared access.
 */

/**
 * COMPARISON: Arena vs Wild vs GC:
 * 
 *                  | Arena       | Wild        | GC
 * -----------------+-------------+-------------+------------
 * Alloc speed      | ~2ns        | ~30ns       | ~10ns
 * Free speed       | O(1) bulk   | ~30ns each  | Automatic
 * Memory overhead  | 0 per-alloc | 16-24 bytes | 8-16 bytes
 * Destructors      | Manual      | Automatic   | Automatic
 * Thread-safe      | No          | Yes         | Yes
 * Use case         | Phases      | C interop   | General
 * 
 * Use Arena when:
 * - Phase-oriented workload (clear reset points)
 * - High allocation frequency
 * - Objects don't need destructors
 * - Extreme performance required
 * 
 * Use Wild when:
 * - C library interop
 * - Manual control needed
 * - Individual deallocation required
 * 
 * Use GC when:
 * - General-purpose allocation
 * - Complex object graphs
 * - Automatic cleanup desired
 */

